\label{section4} In this section, we will use the theory of $L$-series of harmonic Maass forms to establish another summation formula applying to holomorphic cusp forms. The difference from the summation formula of the last section is that it gives an expression for a finite Riesz-type sum, as the summation formula of \cite{BDGRT} did. However, in contrast to \cite{BDGRT}, the formula here is not based on the $L$-series of \cite{ShanSingh22} but on the more general $L$-series of \cite{DLRR23}. In particular, it originates in a different set of test functions which, in turn, works more naturally for non-negative weights $k$. By \eqref{genuine}, when $k \ge 0$, $H'_k(N,\chi)$ includes the elements of $M_k(N, \chi)$ and, in the case of weight $ rac{1}{2},  rac{3}{2}$ and $2$ only, ``genuine" harmonic Maass forms (of polynomial growth). Here, we will consider only the elements of $M_k(N, \chi)$ for even $k$. The family of test functions with which we will work is given by $$\psi_s(t):=\chi_{(0, 1)}(t)(1-t)^{s-1}t^{k-s-1}/\Gamma(s), \, \, 	ext{where $\chi_A$ is the indicator function of the set $A.$}$$ We can then show the following  egin{proposition}\label{anaCont} Let $k \in 2\mathbb N$ and $f \in S_k(N,\chi)$ with $n$-th Fourier coefficient $c(n)$. The $L$-series $L_f(\psi_s)$ converges absolutely in the region $0<\sigma:=\Re(s)<(k-1)/2$, and has an analytic continuation to all $s\in\mathbb{C}$. For all $s \in \mathbb C$, it satisfies the functional equation  egin{equation}\label{FE1} L_f(\psi_s) =i^kN^{1- rac{k}{2}}L_{f|_k w_N}(\psi_s|_{2-k}w_N). \end{equation} \end{proposition}  egin{proof} First, with \cite[(13.4.1)]{DLMF}, followed by an application of \cite[(13.2.39)]{DLMF}, we obtain $$\mathcal{L}\psi_s(2\pi n)= rac{1}{\Gamma(s)}\int_0^1(1-r)^{s-1}r^{k-s-1}e^{-2\pi n r}dr= rac{\Gamma(k-s)}{\Gamma(k)} rac{1}{e^{2\pi n}}M(s, k,2\pi n),$$ where $M(a,b,z)$ is Kummer's confluent hypergeometric function. Since $|\Gamma(s)|(\mathcal{L}|\psi_s|)(2\pi n)=\Gamma(\sigma)(\mathcal{L}\psi_\sigma)(2\pi n),$ the asymptotics $M(a, b, x)=O(x^{a-b}e^{x})$ (\cite{DLMF} (13.7.1)) and $c(n)=O(n^{ rac{k-1}{2}+\varepsilon})$ imply that \eqref{Ff} converges in the region under consideration and we have  egin{equation}\label{lserieslhs} L_{f}(\psi_s)= rac{\Gamma(k-s)}{\Gamma(k)}\sum_{n\geq0} rac{c(n)}{e^{2\pi n}}M(s,k, 2\pi n), \end{equation} To investigate the behaviour of $L_{f|_k w_N}(\psi_s|_{2-k}w_N)$, let the Fourier coefficients of $f|_kw_N$ be denoted by $d(n).$ We note that, for all $s\in\mathbb{C}$, $(\psi_s|_{2-k}w_N)(x)=\chi_{(1/N,\infty)}(x)(Nx-1)^{s-1}/\Gamma(s)$, and hence  egin{equation}\label{LapU} \scrL(\psi_s|_kw_N)(y)= rac{1}{N\Gamma(s)}\int_1^{\infty}(x-1)^{s-1}e^{ rac{-y}{N}x}dx= rac{e^{ rac{-y}{N}}}{N} \left ( rac{y}{N} ight )^{-s}, \end{equation} for all $y>0$. This shows that the holomorphic part of \eqref{Ff} for $f|_kw_N$ and $\psi|_{2-k}w_N$ converges for all $s \in \C$. With \eqref{LapU}, we have  egin{align}\label{kummereqRHSholo} L_{f|_{k}w_N}(\psi_s|_{2-k}w_N)= rac{1}{N} \sum_{n\geq0}d(n)e^{- rac{2\pi n}{N}} \left ( rac{2 \pi n}{N} ight )^{-s}. \end{align} Therefore, for $0<\Re(s)<(k-1)/2$, $\psi_s \in \mathcal F_f$ and $\psi_s|_{2-k}w_N \in \mathcal F_{f|_k w_N}$, and thus, Theorem 4.5 of \cite{DLRR23} holds yielding \eqref{FE1} for all such $s$ in that range. However, we have also shown that $L_{f|_kw_N}(\psi_s|_{2-k}w_N)$ absolutely converges to an analytic function for \emph{all} $s \in \mathbb C$. Therefore, via \eqref{FE1}, $L_f(\psi_s)$ is analytically continued to the entire $s$-plane. \end{proof} We can now state a summation formula for a cusp form, based on the above $L$-series.  egin{theorem} Let $f \in S_k(N, \chi)$ with Fourier coefficients $c(n)$ and denote the Fourier coefficients of $f|_kw_N$ by $d(n).$ Then, for $ho> 1,$ and each $X>0$ we have  egin{multline}\label{SFS3} \sum_{n<X/(2 \pi)} rac{d(n)e^{-2 \pi n}}{(2\pi n)^{ rac{k-1}{2}}} \left (1- rac{2 \pi n}{X} ight )^{ho}= i^{-k}N^{ rac{k}{2}-1} L\left (\psi_{ rac{k-1}{2}} ight ) \+ rac{\Gamma(ho+1)N^{ rac{k}{2}-1}}{2 \pi i^{k+1}\Gamma(k)} \sum_{n>0} rac{c(n)}{e^{2 \pi n}} \int_{(-\varepsilon)}X^{s} rac{\Gamma \left ( rac{k+1}{2}-s ight )\Gamma(s)}{\Gamma(s+ho+1)}M \left ( rac{k-1}{2}+s, k, 2 \pi n ight ) ds. \end{multline} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} For $X>1$, $\varepsilon>0,$ $ho>0$ we consider the integral  egin{equation} \label{Idef} I=\int_{(-\varepsilon)} X^s rac{\Gamma(s)}{\Gamma(s+ho+1)}L_f\left (\psi_{ rac{k-1}{2}+s} ight )ds. \end{equation} By the functional equation \eqref{FE1}, we can express $L_f(\psi_{ rac{k-1}{2}+s})$ as in \eqref{kummereqRHSholo} and we see that  egin{equation}\label{abscon}\sum_{n>0}\int_{(\pm \varepsilon)} \left | X^s  rac{\Gamma(s)}{\Gamma(s+ho+1)} ight |  rac{e^{-2\pi n}|d(n)|}{(2 \pi n)^{ rac{k-1}{2} \pm \varepsilon}}ds \ll X^{\pm \varepsilon} \sum_{n>0}\int_{\mathbb R} (1+|t|)^{-ho-1}e^{-2 \pi n} n^{\varepsilon_1}dt< \infty. \end{equation} Here we used the Stirling formula and the Ramanujan bound for $d(n)$. Therefore, after an application of \eqref{FE1}, we can shift the line of integration to $\varepsilon$, picking up a pole at $s=0$, to obtain  egin{multline} I=i^kN^{1- rac{k}{2}}\int_{(-\varepsilon)} X^s rac{\Gamma(s)}{\Gamma(s+ho+1)}L_{f|_kw_N}\left (\psi_{ rac{k-1}{2}+s}|_{2-k}w_N ight )ds \=i^kN^{1- rac{k}{2}}\int_{(\varepsilon)} X^s rac{\Gamma(s)}{\Gamma(s+ho+1)}L_{f|_k w_N}\left (\psi_{ rac{k-1}{2}+s}|_{2-k} w_N ight )ds- rac{2 \pi i}{\Gamma(ho+1)}L_{f}\left (\psi_{ rac{k-1}{2}} ight ). \end{multline} Because of \eqref{abscon} we can interchange the order of summation in the last integral, so that with \eqref{kummereqRHSholo} and 7.3(20) of \cite{erd} we get $$\int_{(\varepsilon)}  rac{X^s\Gamma(s)}{\Gamma(s+ho+1)}L_{f|_kw_N}\left (\psi_{ rac{k-1}{2}+s}|_{2-k}w_N ight )ds= rac{2 \pi i}{\Gamma(ho+1)}\sum_{n<X/(2 \pi)} rac{d(n)e^{-2 \pi n}}{(2\pi n)^{ rac{k-1}{2}}} \left (1- rac{2 \pi n}{X} ight )^{ho}. $$ On the other hand, by Prop. ef{anaCont}, $(k-1)/2+s$, with $\Re(s)<0$, is in the region of absolute convergence of the $L$-series \eqref{lserieslhs} and thus, once the interchange of summation and integration is justified, equation \eqref{Idef} gives  egin{equation}\label{I2}I= rac{1}{\Gamma(k)} \sum_{n>0} rac{c(n)}{e^{2 \pi n}} \int_{(-\varepsilon)}X^s rac{\Gamma \left ( rac{k+1}{2}-s ight )\Gamma(s)}{\Gamma(s+ho+1)}M \left ( rac{k-1}{2}+s, k, 2 \pi n ight ) ds. \end{equation} Therefore, to complete the proof of the theorem, we only need to show that the interchange of summation and integration is justified. To this end we will need the following uniform bound for $M(a, b, x)$.  egin{lemma}\label{ubound} For $a>0,$ $b>2a+ rac{1}{2}$ and $x \in \mathbb R$, we have $$M\left( a+ ix,\, b,\, y ight) \ll_{a, b, \varepsilon}  rac{e^y y^{a-b+\varepsilon}}{\left | \Gamma\left( a + ix ight) ight |} \quad 	ext{as $y 	o \infty.$}$$ \end{lemma} { f Proof of Lemma.} By (13.14.4), followed by (13.16.4) of \cite{DLMF} we have, for $y>0,$  egin{equation*} M\left( a + ix,\, b,\, y ight) = rac{ e^{ rac{y}{2}}}{y^{ rac{b}{2}}} M_{ rac{b}{2}-a- ix,\,  rac{b-1}{2}} (y) = rac{y^{ rac{1-b}{2}} \Gamma(b)}{\Gamma\left(a + ix ight)} \int_0^{\infty}e^{-t}t^{a- rac{b+1}{2}+ix} I_{b-1}\left(2\sqrt{y t}ight)dt \end{equation*} Set $$M_1:=  rac{y^{ rac{1-b}{2}} \Gamma(b)}{\Gamma\left(a + ix ight)} \int_0^{1}e^{-t}t^{a- rac{b+1}{2}+ix} I_{b-1}\left(2\sqrt{y t}ight)dt $$ and $M_2$ is the corresponding term with integral limits $1$ and $\infty$. Then \cite[(10.40.1)]{DLMF} implies that $$ M_2 \ll  rac{y^{ rac{1-b}{2}}}{\left | \Gamma\left( a+ ix ight) ight |} \int_1^{\infty} e^{-t} t^{a- rac{b+1}{2}}  rac{e^{2\sqrt{yt}}}{(yt)^{ rac14}} dt= rac{y^{ rac14- rac{b}{2}}}{\left | \Gamma\left( a+ ix ight) ight |} \int_1^{\infty} e^{-t+2\sqrt{yt}} t^{a- rac{b}{2}- rac{3}{4}} dt $$ The change of variables $x= \sqrt{t/y}$ shows that  egin{equation}\label{I0} \int_1^{\infty} e^{-t+2\sqrt{yt}} t^{a- rac{b}{2}- rac{3}{4}} dt= 2e^y y^{a- rac{b}{2}+ rac{1}{4}}\int_{ rac{1}{\sqrt{y}}}^{\infty} e^{-y (x-1)^2} x^{2a-b- rac{1}{2}}dx. \end{equation} To bound the integral, we set, for convenience: $$ A = \int_{ rac{1}{r} }^{\infty} e^{-(x-1)^2 r^2} x^{2a-b- rac{1}{2}} \, dx $$ where $r>1,$ and for an $\varepsilon_1>0$, we decompose as  egin{equation}\label{I} A= \left( \int_{1 +  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}}}^{\infty} + \int_{1 -  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}}}^{1 +  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}}} + \int_{ rac{1}{r}}^{1 -  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}}} ight) e^{-(x-1)^2 r^2} x^{2a-b- rac{1}{2}} \, dx \end{equation} For the first and third integral, we note that, since then $|x - 1| > r^{\varepsilon_1-1}$, $$ e^{-(x-1)^2 r^2} x^{2a-b- rac{1}{2}} < e^{- rac{r^2}{r^{2-2\varepsilon_1}}} x^{2a-b- rac{1}{2}} =e^{-r^{2\varepsilon_1}} x^{2a-b- rac{1}{2}} $$ and hence, the first integral of \eqref{I} is:  egin{equation}\label{I1} \le \int_{1 +  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}}}^{\infty} e^{-r^{2\varepsilon_1}} x^{2a-b- rac{1}{2}} dx = e^{-r^{2\varepsilon_1}} \left ( \int_{1 +  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}}}^{\infty} x^{2a-b- rac{1}{2}} dx ight ) =O(e^{-r^{2\varepsilon_1}}) \end{equation} Similarly, the third integral of \eqref{I} is $O(e^{-r^{2\varepsilon_1}})$. For the second integral we have:  egin{multline*} \int_{1 -  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}}}^{1 +  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}}} e^{-(x-1)^2 r^2} x^{2a-b- rac{1}{2}} \, dx \le \int_{1 -  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}}}^{1 +  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}}} x^{2a-b- rac{1}{2}} \, dx \ =  rac{ (1 +  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}})^{2a-b+ rac{1}{2}} - (1 -  rac{1}{r^{1-\varepsilon_1}})^{2a-b+ rac{1}{2}}}{2a-b+ rac{1}{2}}. \end{multline*} By the Taylor expansion of $(1+x)^{2a-b+ rac{1}{2}}$ at $x=0,$ we deduce that this is $O(r^{-1+\varepsilon_1}).$ Comparing with \eqref{I1}, we see that this bound dominates as $r 	o \infty.$ Therefore, $A=O(r^{-1+\varepsilon_1})$, which we can apply to \eqref{I0} with $r=\sqrt{y}$, to deduce that  egin{equation}\label{M2b} M_2 \ll  rac{y^{ rac14- rac{b}{2}}e^{y } y^{a- rac{b}{2}+ rac14}y^{- rac12+ rac12 \varepsilon_1}}{\left | \Gamma\left( a + ix ight) ight |}= rac{e^y y^{a-b+ rac12 \varepsilon_1}}{\left | \Gamma\left( a + ix ight) ight |}. \end{equation} To bound $M_1$, we note that, by the series definitions of $I_
u$ and $J_{
u}$, we have $|I_{b-1}\left(2\sqrt{2\pi nt}ight)|=|J_{b-1}\left(2i\sqrt{2\pi nt}ight)|$. This, combined with inequality $|J_{
u}(z)| \le |z/2|^{
u}e^{|\Im(z)|}/\Gamma(
u+1)$, valid for $
u \ge -1/2$ (\cite[(10.14.4)]{DLMF}) implies that $$M_1 \ll  rac{y^{ rac{1-b}{2}}}{|\Gamma\left(a + ix ight)|} \int_0^{1}e^{-t}t^{a- rac{b+1}{2}} (yt)^{ rac{b-1}{2}} e^{2 \sqrt{yt}}dt\le  rac{ e^{2\sqrt{y}}}{|\Gamma\left(a + ix ight)|} \int_0^{1}e^{-t} t^{a-1}dt. $$ Comparing this with \eqref{M2b} we deduce the lemma. \qed We can apply this lemma with $y=2 \pi n$, $a= rac{k-1}{2}-\varepsilon$ and $b=k$ to get, with $c(n) \ll n^{ rac{k-1}{2}+\varepsilon_2}$,  egin{multline}\label{|I21|} \sum_{n>0} rac{|c(n)|}{e^{2 \pi n}}\int_{\mathbb R} \left |  rac{\Gamma \left ( rac{k+1}{2}+\varepsilon-ix ight )\Gamma(-\varepsilon+ix)}{\Gamma(-\varepsilon+ho+1+ix)} ight | \left | M \left ( rac{k-1}{2}-\varepsilon+ix, k, 2 \pi n ight ) ight |dx \ \ll \sum_{n>0} rac{n^{ rac{k-1}{2}+\varepsilon_2- rac{k}{2}- rac12-\varepsilon+\varepsilon_1} e^{2 \pi n}}{e^{2 \pi n}} \int_{\mathbb R} \left |  rac{\Gamma \left ( rac{k+1}{2}+\varepsilon-ix ight )\Gamma(-\varepsilon+ix)}{\Gamma(-\varepsilon+ho+1+ix) \Gamma\left(  rac{k-1}{2} - \varepsilon + ix ight)} ight | dx. \end{multline} For $\varepsilon_1, \varepsilon_2$ such that $\varepsilon_2+\varepsilon_1<\varepsilon$ the series converges and, by Stirling, $$\left |  rac{\Gamma \left ( rac{k+1}{2}+\varepsilon-ix ight )\Gamma(-\varepsilon+ix)}{\Gamma(-\varepsilon+ho+1+ix) \Gamma\left(  rac{k-1}{2} - \varepsilon + ix ight)} ight | \ll (1+|x|)^{2\varepsilon-ho}.$$ For $ho>1$, this shows that \eqref{|I21|} converges as required. \end{proof}  egin{corollary} With the assumptions of the theorem, we have, for $ho> 1$ and each $X>0$,  egin{equation} \sum_{n<X/(2 \pi)} rac{d(n)e^{-2 \pi n}}{(2\pi n)^{ rac{k-1}{2}}} \left (1- rac{2 \pi n}{X} ight )^{ho}= i^{-k}N^{ rac{k}{2}-1} L\left (\psi_{ rac{k-1}{2}} ight )+O(X^{-\varepsilon}). \end{equation} \end{corollary}  egin{proof} This follows once we apply Lemma ef{ubound} to the last term of \eqref{SFS3} as we did in ef{|I21|}. \end{proof} \iffalse

